# Data Visualization: Animation

We first create an animation of the time evolution of 4 different distributions: f, Gumbel, Laplace and normal, depending on the number of samples.


```python
'''
Note: the code takes 10 to 15 minutes to compile due to the number of frames
'''

%matplotlib notebook
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import matplotlib as mpl
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.animation as animation

distribution, colors = ['f', 'Gumbel', 'Laplace', 'normal'], ['#8FB9EA', '#9FEA8F', '#EADB8F', '#EA8FE2']

'''We create the update fuction'''

def update(curr):
    if curr == n:
        a.event_source.stop()

    for i in range(len(axs)):
        axs[i].cla()
        
    '''
    Set chart sizes 
    '''

    axs[0].axis([-0.5,8,0,80])
    axs[1].axis([-20,80,0,40])
    axs[2].axis([-25,25,0,60])
    axs[3].axis([-15,15,0,40])
    
    '''
    Create bar charts
    '''

    for i in range(1,len(axs)+1):
        axs[i-1].hist(globals()['x{}'.format(i)][:curr], 
                      bins=globals()['bins{}'.format(i)], 
                      color=colors[i-1])
        
        axs[i-1].set_title('{} distribution'.format(distribution[i-1]), 
                           fontsize=10, 
                           pad=4)

'''
We create this function to adjust the position of the bottom plots
'''

def position(axs):
    pos = axs.get_position().bounds
    exit_lst = []
    for i in range(len(pos)):
        exit_lst.append(pos[i])
    exit_lst[1] = exit_lst[1] - 0.05
    return exit_lst

'''
Create and adjust figure
'''

fig, ((ax1, ax2), (ax3, ax4)) = plt.subplots(2, 2)
fig.suptitle('Understanding Distributions Through Sampling: Animation', fontsize=12, weight='bold')
axs = [ax1, ax2, ax3, ax4]
n = 1000

'''
Adjust the position of the bottom plots
'''

ax3.set_position(position(ax3))
ax4.set_position(position(ax4))

'''
We create the artificial datasets
'''

x1 = np.random.f(2, 100, n)
x2 = np.random.gumbel(0, 10, n)
x3 = np.random.laplace(0, 5, n)
x4 = np.random.normal(0, 5, n)

'''
Set bins sizes for each chart
'''

bins1 = np.arange(0, 6, 0.06)
bins2 = np.arange(-20, 60, 0.7)
bins3 = np.arange(-20, 20, 0.5)
bins4 = np.arange(-10, 10, 0.3)

'''
Save animation as gif
'''

anim = animation.FuncAnimation(fig, 
                               update, 
                               interval=30, 
                               frames=1000)

anim.save('prueba.gif', 
          writer='imagemagick')
```

# Data Visualization: Widgets

In this figure we are going to create 4 bar graphs where each one represents a different distribution: f, Gumbel, Laplace and normal. We will add a slider bar where we can set the number of samples of each distribution and see how they behave.


```python
%matplotlib notebook
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from matplotlib.widgets import Slider, Button
from matplotlib.transforms import Bbox

'''
We create the update function
'''

def update(val):
    n_sample = round(sn.val)
    
    '''
    Artificial datasets
    '''

    x1 = np.random.f(2, 100, n_sample)
    x2 = np.random.gumbel(0, 10, n_sample)
    x3 = np.random.laplace(0, 5, n_sample)
    x4 = np.random.normal(0, 5, n_sample)
    
    '''
    Updating bar charts
    '''

    ax1.cla()
    ax2.cla()
    ax3.cla()
    ax4.cla()

    ax1.hist(x1, bins=bins1, color='#8FB9EA')
    ax2.hist(x2, bins=bins2, color='#9FEA8F')
    ax3.hist(x3, bins=bins3, color='#EADB8F')
    ax4.hist(x4, bins=bins4, color='#EA8FE2')

    ax1.set_title('f distribution', fontsize=10, pad=4)
    ax2.set_title('Gumbel distribution', fontsize=10, pad=4)
    ax3.set_title('Laplace distribution', fontsize=10, pad=4)
    ax4.set_title('Normal distribution', fontsize=10, pad=4)

    fig.canvas.draw_idle()

'''
Set function to reset the charts
'''    
    
def reset(event):
    sn.reset()

'''
function to adjust the position of the bottom plots
'''

def position(axs):
    pos = axs.get_position().bounds
    exit_lst = []
    for i in range(len(pos)):
        exit_lst.append(pos[i])
    exit_lst[1] = exit_lst[1]-0.05
    return exit_lst

'''
Create and adjust figure
'''

fig, ((ax1, ax2), (ax3, ax4)) = plt.subplots(2, 2)
fig.suptitle('Understanding Distributions Through Sampling: Widgets', 
             fontsize=12, 
             weight='bold')
axs = [ax1, ax2, ax3, ax4]
plt.subplots_adjust(bottom=0.25)

'''
Initial conditions
'''

x1 = np.random.f(2, 100, 1000)
x2 = np.random.gumbel(0, 10, 1000)
x3 = np.random.laplace(0, 5, 1000)
x4 = np.random.normal(0, 5, 1000)

ax3.set_position(position(ax3))
ax4.set_position(position(ax4))

bins1 = np.arange(0, 6, 0.06)
bins2 = np.arange(-20, 60, 0.7)
bins3 = np.arange(-20, 20, 0.5)
bins4 = np.arange(-10, 10, 0.3)

distribution, colors = ['f', 'Gumbel', 'Laplace', 'normal'], ['#8FB9EA', '#9FEA8F', '#EADB8F', '#EA8FE2']

for i in range(1,len(axs)+1):
    axs[i-1].hist(globals()['x{}'.format(i)], 
                  bins=globals()['bins{}'.format(i)], 
                  color=colors[i-1])
    
    axs[i-1].set_title('{} distribution'.format(distribution[i-1]), 
                       fontsize=10, 
                       pad=4)
    
'''
Create the slider
'''

sn = Slider(ax = plt.axes([0.19, 0.09, 0.65, 0.03]),
            label = 'n Sample',
            valmin = 10,
            valmax = 10000,
            valinit = 100)

sn.on_changed(update)

'''
Reset buttom
'''

resetax = plt.axes([0.8, 0.025, 0.1, 0.04])
button = Button(resetax, 'Reset', hovercolor='#5155CC')
button.on_clicked(reset)


plt.show();
```
